<DOC><DOCNO> AP880919-0179 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 0843EDT</FILEID><FIRST>a a BC-History Adv26   09-19 0523</FIRST><SECOND>BC-History, Adv 26,0543</SECOND><NOTE>$adv26</NOTE><NOTE>For release Monday, Sept. 26</NOTE><HEAD>Today in History</HEAD><HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD><TEXT>   Today is Monday, Sept. 26, the 270th day of 1988. There are 96days left in the year.   Today's highlight in history:   In 1888, poet, dramatist and critic T.S. Eliot was born in St.Louis. Eliot would become one of the most distinguished literaryfigures of the 20th century, writing such famous poems as ``TheWaste Land'' and ``The Love Song of J. Alfred Prufrock,'' andwinning the Nobel Prize for literature in 1948. Eliot, who became aBritish subject in 1927, died in 1965.   On this date:   In 1777, British troops occupied Philadelphia in the AmericanRevolution.   In 1789, Thomas Jefferson was appointed America's firstsecretary of state; John Jay was named the first chief justice ofthe U.S. Supreme Court; Samuel Osgood began service as the firstpostmaster general; and Edmund Jennings Randolph was named thefirst attorney general.   In 1820, pioneer Daniel Boone died in Missouri at 85.   In 1892, John Philip Sousa and his band performed in public forthe first time, in Plainfield, N.J.   In 1898, composer George Gershwin was born in New York.   In 1914, the Federal Trade Commission was established.   In 1918, the Meuse-Argonne offensive against the Germans beganduring World War I.   In 1950, U.N. troops in the Korean War recaptured the SouthKorean capital of Seoul from the North Koreans.   In 1955, following word that President Dwight D. Eisenhower hadsuffered a heart attack, the New York Stock Exchange saw its worstprice decline since 1929.   In 1957, the musical ``West Side Story'' opened on Broadway.   In 1960, the first of four televised debates betweenpresidential candidates Richard M. Nixon and John F. Kennedy tookplace in Chicago.   In 1962, ``The Beverly Hillbillies'' premiered on CBS-TV.   In 1968, ``Hawaii Five-O'' made its debut as an hourly programon CBS, having premiered as a two-hour movie the week before.   In 1977, Sir Freddie Laker began his cut-rate Skytrain servicefrom London to New York. The carrier went out of business in 1982.   Ten years ago: Railroad clerks went on strike, halting more thantwo-thirds of the nation's rail service for four days until theunion representing the clerks complied with a federal court orderfor a cooling-off period.   Five years ago: In an address to the United Nations, PresidentReagan said ``the door to an agreement is open'' concerningintermediate-range nuclear missiles in Europe. Australia II becamethe first challenger to win the America's Cup as a team led by JohnBertrand defeated the Liberty, skippered by Dennis Conner, in theseventh and deciding race on Rhode Island Sound.   One year ago: In his weekly radio address, President Reagan saidhe was reluctantly signing legislation restoring the automaticdeficit-reducing provisions of the Gramm-Rudman Act.   Today's birthdays: Actress Julie London is 62. Actor PatrickO'Neal is 61. Actor Kent McCord is 46. Singer Lynn Anderson is 41.Singer Olivia Newton-John is 40. Actress Melissa Sue Anderson is 26.   Thought for today: ``This is the way the world ends@ Not with abang but a whimper.'' _ T.S. Eliot.</TEXT></DOC>